frameDefinitions: A Mass_theme, generally made up of many individuals, moves from a Source to a Goal with some Path.
An Entity has a particular scalar Attribute with a value exceeding a contextually-specified or generally-understood standard.
An Entity has a Sharpness characterized by its capability to cut.
This frame covers descriptions of an entire human body, viewed as a gestalt (as opposed to descriptions based on salient body parts).
Using Evidence, which may or may not be expressed, a Cognizer recognizes or proves that Concept1 is associated causally or collocationally with another concept, Concept2.
An Agent or Cause makes a Patient sharper or duller.
frameExamples: Emails from so-called Nigerian princes <t>flooded</t> inboxes all over the US.
John is in the basement <t>sharpening</t> his axe.
listRoleDefinitions: The mass of entities which moves.
The place where the overall motion event takes place, thus including Source, Path, and Goal locations.
The Source is the location the Theme occupies initially before its change of location.
Path refers to (a part of the) ground the <fen>Mass_theme</fen> travels over or to a landmark the <fen>Mass_theme</fen> travels by.
Goal is the location the <fen>Mass_theme</fen> ends up in.

This role is used for expressions that indicate motion along a line from the deitic center towards a reference point (which may be implicit) that is neither the <fen>Goal</fen> of the posture change nor a landmark along the way of the moving part of the body.  Often <fen>Direction</fen> is defined with reference to the canonical orientation of the <fen>Mass_theme</fen>, or the orientation imposed by an implicit observer.
When the event occurs.
The spatial setting in which the Mass_motion takes place.
The <fen>Entity</fen> for which a particular gradable <fen>Attribute</fen> is appropriate and under consideration.
The feature of an <fen>Entity</fen> which is under discussion.
A quantity or other characterization of the <fen>Entity</fen>'s state with respect to the <fen>Attribute</fen>.
A modifier expressing  the deviation of the <fen>Value</fen> from the norm.
The <fen>Time</fen> during which the <fen>Entity</fen> is in the state of having  a particular <fen>Value</fen> for the <fen>Attribute</fen>.
The <fen>Entity</fen> to which the <fen>Sharpness</fen> attribute is related.
The sharpness feature of the <fen>Entity</fen>.
A modifier expressing  the deviation of the <fen>Sharpness</fen> from the norm or from the value for another <fen>Entity</fen>.
The <fen>Sharpness</fen> value of the <fen>Entity</fen>.  This role is denoted by the adjectives of the frame.
The <fen>Time</fen> during which the <fen>Entity</fen> is in the state of having  a particular value for <fen>Sharpness</fen>.
This role identifies the individual (or individuals) being described.
This role identifies the <fen>Figure</fen> or form being described by the target.
<fen>Concept1</fen> is the phenomenon which is believed to be related to <fen>Concept2</fen>.
The phenomenon which is believed to be linked to Concept1.
The sentient entity that recognizes the causal connection.
The phenomena which are believed to be related.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Cognizer</fen> make the connection.
The location where the Cognizer makes the connection.
The <fen>Agent</fen> causes the <fen>Patient</fen> to become more or less sharp.
The <fen>Patient</fen> is the entity that is sharpened.
An animate or inanimate entity, a force, or event that produces the state of sharpness.  Volitionality is not a necessary characteristic of <fen>Cause</fen>s.
This role identifies the time when the <fen>Agent</fen> sharpens <fen>Patient</fen>.
This role identifies the place where the <fen>Agent</fen> sharpens the <fen>Patient</fen>.
listRoleExamples: Letters streamed in <fex>all over the country</fex>.
Afterwards, the crowd flooded <fex>away from the ceremony</fex>.
The door opened , and a crowd of people flooded <fex>past me</fex>, into the hall.
<fex>In the main auditorium</fex> people crowded around Orange's newest computer
<fex>The smith</fex> sharpened many knives in the days before the war.
Several cuts into the log had dulled <fex>the blade</fex>.
<fex>The relentless impacts against the wood</fex> gradually blunted the edge of this axe.
